Explanation
To solve the problem, we will use a Dynamic Programming (DP) approach. Let dp[i][j] be the minimum number of steps required to reach the i-th position in the column j.

We can calculate dp[i][j] as follows:

If j is odd, then dp[i][j] = min(dp[i-1][j-1], dp[i-1][j+1]) + abs(a[i][j] - a[i][j-1]).
If j is even, then dp[i][j] = min(dp[i-1][j-1], dp[i-1][j+1]) + abs(a[i][j] - a[i][j+1]).
If j is at the boundary of the column, then dp[i][j] = min(dp[i-1][j-1], dp[i-1][j+1]) + abs(a[i][j] - 0).
Initialize dp[0][0] = 0.

Compute dp[1][1] and dp[1][2] as follows:

If j is odd, then dp[1][j] = abs(a[1][j] - a[1][j-1]).
If j is even, then dp[1][j] = abs(a[1][j] - a[1][j+1]).
If j is at the boundary of the column, then dp[1][j] = abs(a[1][j] - 0).

Repeat the above steps for i from 2 to n-1 and j from 1 to m.

The final answer will be the minimum value among the dp[n-1][1], dp[n-1][2], ..., dp[n-1][m] values.

Complexity
The time complexity of the solution is O(nm), and the space complexity is O(m).

