## Problem Statement

You are given a string s consisting of n lowercase Latin letters.

Let's call a substring of s good if the number of distinct characters in this substring is equal to the number of distinct characters in s. For example, if s = "abacaba", then the substrings "a", "b", "c", "a", "b", "a", "baca" and "acaba" are good and the substrings "aa", "bb", "c", "aba" and "baba" are not good.

Your task is to find the number of good substrings in s.

## Input

The first line of the input contains a single integer n (1 ≤ n ≤ 105) — the length of the string s.

The second line of the input contains a string s consisting of n lowercase Latin letters.

## Output

Print one integer — the number of good substrings in s.

## Examples

inputCopy
5
abacab
outputCopy
10
inputCopy
10
aaaaaaaaaa
outputCopy
55

## Note

In the first example, the good substrings are "a", "b", "c", "a", "b", "a", "baca", "acaba", "bacab" and "acab".

In the second example, the good substrings are "a", "aa", "aaa", "aaaa", "aaaaa", "aaaaaa", "aaaaaaa", "aaaaaaaa", "aaaaaaaaa" and "aaaaaaaaaa".

## Solution

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int n;
    cin >> n;
    string s;
    cin >> s;
    int ans = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        int cnt[26] = {0};
        for (int j = i; j < n; j++) {
            cnt[s[j] - 'a']++;
            int distinct = 0;
            for (int k = 0; k < 26; k++) {
                if (cnt[k] > 0) {
                    distinct++;
                }
            }
            if (distinct == j - i + 1) {
                ans++;
            }
        }
    }
    cout << ans << endl;
    return 0;
}
```

## Complexity

Time complexity: O(n^2)

Space complexity: O(1)

## Conclusion

This problem is a good example of how to use the sliding window technique to solve a problem. The solution is simple and easy to understand.

