## Problem Statement

You are given a string s consisting of n lowercase Latin letters.

You can perform the following operation any number of times (possibly zero):

Choose a substring of s that consists of at least two consecutive letters and remove them from s.
For example, if s = "abacaba", then the following substrings of s are valid: "a", "b", "a", "c", "a", "b", "a", "a", "b", "a", "c", "a", "b", "a", "a", "b", "a", "c", "a", "b", "a".

Your task is to find the maximum possible length of the resulting string.

## Input

The first line of the input contains a single integer t (1≤t≤1000) — the number of test cases.

The first and only line of each test case contains a string s (2≤|s|≤100), consisting of lowercase Latin letters.

## Output

For each test case, print the maximum possible length of the resulting string.

## Example

inputCopy
3
abacaba
abacabaabacaba
abacabaabacabaabacaba
outputCopy
0
7
14
Note
In the first test case, the only valid substring is "a", so the resulting string is empty.

In the second test case, the only valid substrings are "a", "b", "a", "c", "a", "b", "a".

In the third test case, the only valid substrings are "a", "b", "a", "c", "a", "b", "a", "a", "b", "a", "c", "a", "b", "a".

## Solution

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int t;
    cin >> t;
    while (t--) {
        string s;
        cin >> s;
        int n = s.length();
        int ans = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            int j = i;
            while (j < n && s[j] == s[i]) {
                j++;
            }
            ans = max(ans, j - i);
            i = j - 1;
        }
        cout << ans << endl;
    }
    return 0;
}
```

## Complexity

Time complexity: O(n)

Space complexity: O(1)

## Conclusion

This problem is a good example of how to use the sliding window technique to solve a problem. The solution is simple and easy to understand.

