## 1. Problem Statement

You are given a string s consisting of lowercase English letters. You can perform the following operation on the string any number of times:

Choose any two adjacent distinct characters in the string and swap them.
For example, if the string is "abcd", you can swap the characters 'a' and 'b' to get "bacd".

Find the lexicographically smallest string you can obtain by performing the above operation any number of times.

## 2. Input Format

The first line of input contains a single integer t (1≤t≤100) — the number of test cases.

The first and only line of each test case contains a string s (2≤|s|≤100), consisting of lowercase English letters.

## 3. Output Format

For each test case, print the lexicographically smallest string you can obtain by performing the above operation any number of times.

## 4. Constraints

1≤t≤100
2≤|s|≤100
s consists of lowercase English letters.

## 5. Sample Input 1

```
3
ab
aa
zz
```

## 6. Sample Output 1

```
ab
aa
az
```

## 7. Explanation

In the first test case, you can swap the characters 'a' and 'b' to get "ab".

In the second test case, you can swap the characters 'a' and 'a' to get "aa".

In the third test case, you can swap the characters 'z' and 'z' to get "az".

## 8. Solution

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int t;
    cin >> t;
    while (t--) {
        string s;
        cin >> s;
        int n = s.length();
        for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
            if (s[i] > s[i + 1]) {
                swap(s[i], s[i + 1]);
                break;
            }
        }
        cout << s << endl;
    }
    return 0;
}
```

## 9. Complexity Analysis

Time complexity: O(n)
Space complexity: O(1)

